knowledge_graph.title: Orange roughy
knowledge_graph.description: The orange roughy, also known as the red roughy, slimehead and deep sea perch, is a relatively large deep-sea fish belonging to the slimehead family. The UK Marine Conservation Society has categorized orange roughy as "vulnerable to exploitation".

related_questions.question: Why is the orange roughy on the avoid list?
related_questions.snippet: Forest & Bird (NZ) rank Orange Roughy E (RED - AVOID) in their Best Fish Guide. Orange Roughy has the worst ecological ranking of any commercial fishery in the Best Fish Guide As a long lived, deep water species Orange Roughy is extremely vulnerable to overfishing.

related_questions.question: Is orange roughy the same as tilapia?
related_questions.snippet: No. Although they are both a white fish, Orange Roughy is a much higher quality of fish. A Talapia is a low cost and lower quality of fish. Talapia can have a high amount of metals from the polluted waters they swim in.

related_questions.question: Why is orange roughy hard to find?
related_questions.snippet: Many orange roughy stocks have already crashed, namely in New Zealand and Australia where they were first exploited in the late 1970s; and recently discovered stocks are decreasing rapidly. The fish are slow growing, late maturing and difficult to recover once depleted due to these life history characteristics.
